  "text": "The AQL query execution pipeline in ArangoDB follows these key stages:\n\n1. **Parsing Stage (arangod/Aql/Parser.cpp)**: The Parser class (defined in Parser.h) is responsible for lexical and syntactic analysis of AQL query strings. It converts the query text into an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) that represents the query structure.\n\n2. **Optimization Stage (arangod/Aql/Optimizer.cpp)**: The Optimizer class (Optimizer.h) transforms the initial AST into an optimized ExecutionPlan. It applies various optimization rules (OptimizerRules) to reduce query complexity and improve performance by reordering operations, eliminating redundant work, and choosing efficient access paths.\n\n3. **Execution Engine (arangod/Aql/ExecutionEngine.cpp)**: The ExecutionEngine class (ExecutionEngine.h) is the runtime engine that manages query execution. It instantiates ExecutionBlocks from the execution plan and coordinates the execution flow, managing asynchronous operations, handling result collection, and controlling query lifecycle.\n\n4. **Execution Blocks (arangod/Aql/ExecutionBlock.cpp)**: The ExecutionBlock class (ExecutionBlock.h) is the fundamental building block of query execution. Each ExecutionNode in the plan is wrapped in an ExecutionBlock that implements specific operations (collection scans, filters, joins, aggregations, etc.). These blocks form a pipeline that processes data row-by-row or in batches.\n\n5. **Storage Engine Interface (arangod/RocksDBEngine/RocksDBCollection.cpp)**: The RocksDBCollection class (RocksDBCollection.h) provides the interface to the RocksDB storage engine for actual data retrieval. It handles document lookups, index access, and iteration over collections, translating high-level data access requests from ExecutionBlocks into RocksDB operations.\n\n6. **Transaction Management (arangod/Transaction/Manager.cpp & Context.cpp)**: The Manager class (Manager.h) tracks and manages transaction state, while the Context class (Context.h) provides the transaction context for query execution. These classes ensure ACID properties and manage transaction lifecycle, isolation levels, and conflict detection during query execution."
}

